t to me. Just make sure the validation error type is its own `WaitingOnError` (not reusing `TodoTitleError`) since it's a different domain concept with potentially different constraints.\n\n**5. `from_parts` reconstruction**\n\nMake sure the `from_parts` factory method uses `resolved_at: Option<DateTime<Utc>>` (not `completed_at`) and returns `Active` when `None`, `Resolved` when `Some(...)`. Same pattern as NextAction but with the correct domain terminology.\n\n### Nice-to-have\n\n**6. Consider whether \"convert to Next Action\" belongs in the WaitingForItem domain type or as a service-level workflow**\n\nYou've correctly deferred this to a follow-up, which I support. When we do implement it, the conversion should be a service-level operation (not a method on `WaitingForItem`) because it crosses aggregate boundaries -- it needs to create a NextAction (which requires a context selection) and delete/resolve the WaitingForItem. The domain type itself should not know about NextAction.\n\n### Summary of domain type I'd expect to see:\n\n```\nWaitingForId(Uuid)     -- newtype, same pattern as ProjectId\nWaitingOn              -- newtype, non-empty, max 100 chars, trimmed, parse() constructor\nWaitingOnError         -- Empty / TooLong { max, actual }\nWaitingForItem         -- enum: Active { id, user_id, title, waiting_on, created_at }\n                                Resolved { ..., resolved_at }\n                       -- methods: resolve() -> Self, accessors\n```\n\nThe rest of your design (routes, templates, HTMX, TDD approach) looks well-aligned with our patterns. Looking forward to reviewing the implementation."
